    <p>A former defense contractor employee in California has filed a lawsuit alleging that he lost his job because he refused to perform illegal tasks. The man, who is a retired naval officer, says that he was the victim of <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Wrongful-Termination/Retaliation.shtml" >employer retaliation</a> after he refused illegal orders from his boss at Systems Application and Technologies, Inc. The suit comes at a devastating time for the company, which has just been accused of operating a malfunctioning drone that caused $30 million in damage to Naval equipment.</p> <p>The plaintiff argues that his supervisor instructed him to work on weekends without compensation. That was just one piece of evidence that demonstrated the company's general incompetence, according to the former employee. The man was employed by SA-Tech to oversee a drone project that provided targets for aerial training at California military facilities.</p>
    <p>Shortly after the man was hired on to the project, he realized that the company was lacking materials and funding needed to complete critical operations tasks. At that time, the man's supervisor apparently refused to transfer additional money to the project. That meant that workers were denied pay for 60 days -- until a government contract could be finalized.</p> <p>Further, the man claims that he had told the company that drone operators were not properly trained or certified, and that they could pose a threat to public safety. Indeed, that proved to be the case; one of the company's out-of-control drones punched a hole in a Naval vessel and started a fire on board, wounding two sailors. That incident was blamed on a combination of human error and system failures.</p> <p>After that mishap, the man says that he was told to work over a weekend, but his supervisor instructed him to leave the hours off of his time card. Such actions are considered illegal. No matter the industry, no one should be subject to retaliatory acts for refusing to work without pay. All workers deserve fair compensation, which they may pursue in an employment lawsuit if their company does not comply.</p> <p><b>Source:</b> Courthouse News Service, "<a href="http://www.courthousenews.com/2014/08/22/70684.htm" target="_blank">Navy Contractor Accused of Retaliatory Firing</a>" Dan McCue, Aug. 22, 2014</p>
