    <p>Did you know that California workers are guaranteed certain rights at their place of employment? The California Department of Fair Employment and Housing is responsible for enforcing the laws that protect employees from various types of <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Discrimination/" >workplace discrimination</a>. These rules are designed to shield workers from unfair treatment and provide them with a respectful, safe working environment.</p> <p>You may be surprised at the multitude of categories that exist for employment discrimination. Workers in California are protected from unfair treatment based on their race and ethnicity, but employees' religion, health status, marital status, disabilities and sexual orientation are also considered protected categories. Further, sex discrimination is prohibited; that means that an employer cannot discriminate based on pregnancy status or requests for breastfeeding.</p>
    <p>Employers are responsible for prohibiting harassment at their work sites. Harassment should never occur against employees or those applying for employment. Further, independent contractors are shielded from workplace harassment and employment discrimination -- many states do not extend such protections. These requirements are dictated by the California Fair Employment and Housing Act and associated regulations.</p> <p>Job applicants and current employees may be entitled to file a complaint with the DFEH if they believe they have been the victims of workplace discrimination. Independent contractors may also be eligible for this action. California law provides specific remedies for those who have suffered because of legal violations. Those include remedies such as the provision of back pay, reinstatement to a former position, promotion and hiring. Employers may also be required to pay punitive damages and compensate victims for their emotional distress.</p> <p>These claims are restricted by statutes of limitations for filing, however. Complaints must be submitted to the DFEH within a year of the last instance of harassment or discrimination. For workers under the age of 18, the limit extends to a year after the victim's eighteenth birthday. Quick action on the part of the injured employee may improve the chances of recovering damages in a harassment case.</p> <p><b>Source:</b> California Department of Fair Employment and Housing, "<a href="http://www.dfeh.ca.gov/res/docs/Publications/DFEH-162.pdf.pdf" target="_blank">California Law Prohibits Workplace Discrimination and Harassment</a>" Aug. 19, 2014</p>
