    <p>Should you be passed up for a promotion because you took time off to care for a sick relative? Although federal mandates protect workers who need to take time off for maternity leave or an extended illness, employers do not always follow the rules. Experts in California and other states say they are seeing an upswing in the number of lawsuits that have been filed against employers who fail to comply with the <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Discrimination/FMLA.shtml" >Family and Medical Leave Act</a>.</p> <p>Employees do not have to meet a massive legal standard in order to prove employment law violations related to FMLA provisions. In fact, FMLA complaints only have to prove that the employer deterred the worker from taking leave that is authorized under the legislation. Further, employers who interrupt such a leave -- by calling a worker back in during maternity leave, for example -- can also be considered violators.</p>
    <p>The uptick in FMLA lawsuits may be a direct effect of increased education about employee rights. FMLA matters are more commonly discussed in the modern workplace, so more employees are aware of their options under the act. Those employees are demanding fair treatment -- and they are winning lawsuits.</p> <p>Workers can be entitled to a significant amount of money in connection with an FMLA suit. They can recover up to double any of their wages that were lost. Additional claims can also recover damages for the cost of caring for an ill family member if leave is denied. Punitive damages are not available to workers under this law, however.</p> <p>Federal legislation protecting workers' health and welfare exists for a reason. Employers who negligently refuse to recognize family illness or personal illness as a legitimate reason to take leave should be held accountable. Workers deserve to exercise the full panel of protections provided under the FMLA.</p> <p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b> The Wall Street Journal, "<a href="http://online.wsj.com/articles/more-workers-file-family-leave-lawsuits-1407515411" target="_blank">More Workers File Family-Leave Lawsuits</a>" Joe Palazzolo, Aug. 08, 2014 </p>
