    <p>If you have reported an incident of workplace discrimination, you may be concerned about the backlash of emotions that could come from your supervisors or higher-ups at your company. Finding yourself in this situation can be unnerving, but it is important to understand that you have legal protections under both California and federal law. <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Wrongful-Termination/Retaliation.shtml" >Employer retaliation</a> against a whistleblower is illegal. Victims should never have to endure intimidation, threats, coercion or harassment because they have spoken out against a discriminatory practice.</p> <p>Retaliation at a California workplace occurs when three factors combine. The employer must take an adverse action against an employee, also known as a covered individual, because that person participated in a protected activity. Just what constitutes a protected activity? Legal experts say that employees should never be targeted by their supervisors for informing an employer in good faith that they believe discrimination is occurring. Everything from picketing to filing a formal complaint and refusing to obey a discriminatory order would fall into this category. Serving as a witness in a federal employment investigation is also considered a protected activity.</p>
    <p>Covered individuals in this case include those who oppose unlawful practices and have sought help for employment discrimination. Those who have a close association with the person claiming discrimination are also covered -- that includes spouses, children and others. Keep in mind that whistleblowers who have raised ethical concerns not related to discrimination are not considered protected parties.</p> <p>Finally, the employer must take adverse action against the person complaining of discrimination. These actions may include demotion, refusal to hire or termination. Threats, unfair performance reviews and increased surveillance would also fall into this category. Victims who have suffered from this type of treatment on the job after enduring discrimination deserve financial compensation for their travails. Everyone has a right to a harassment-free workplace.</p> <p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b> U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, "<a href="http://www.eeoc.gov/laws/types/facts-retal.cfm" target="_blank">Facts About Retaliation</a>" Aug. 06, 2014 </p>
