    <p>A woman who had managed a Chipotle Mexican Grill in San Luis Obispo, California, is seeking financial compensation for workplace discrimination and violations of her employee rights. The woman, who filed the lawsuit in March, accuses her former employer of race discrimination, along with hour and wage violations. Further, she claims that she was denied opportunities for advancement. The woman is African-American.</p> <p>The woman said she faced resistance at work when she lobbied for fair break times for employees. Further, she argues that she and several other employees suffered constant harassment from their former supervisor, who made discriminatory comments about her race. She also has accused that supervisor of publicly shaming her by cursing at her. That man is also said to have filled a worker's lemonade drink with salt, causing the worker to become violently ill.</p>
    <p>The woman's attorney said she approached him while she was still working at the restaurant. She was looking for help with potential hour and wage violations that were occurring at the restaurant. The woman was able to join a larger class-action lawsuit in addition to the discrimination claims -- that larger suit alleges that the restaurant chain committed wage violations by improperly classifying managers as exempt from overtime pay. The company is also accused of reporting violations with regards to employee wages, which may result in tax discrepancies, according to state and federal sources.</p> <p>No one should have to suffer such indignities when they go to do their job. Race discrimination and other types of negative treatment have no place in our modern working world. Those who have been victimized by systematic discrimination and abuse deserve financial compensation for their troubles.</p> <p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b> The Tribune, "<a href="http://www.sanluisobispo.com/2014/07/25/3168133/chipotle-lawsuit-janeka-samuels.html" target="_blank">Ex-manager at SLO Chipotle claims discrimination, labor law violations</a>" Matt Fountain, Jul. 25, 2014 </p>
