    <p>A former manager at Twitter is taking legal action against the social media company after he was allegedly fired because of his age. The man, age 57, is also accusing the company of violating <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Discrimination/" >workplace discrimination</a> regulations by terminating his employment because of a physical disability. That man had been the head of data center deployment for the high-profile organization, which is based in San Francisco.</p> <p>The suit alleges that the man's supervisor made critical comments about his age. Further, documents note that Twitter staff are generally young, with few out of their 30s. The plaintiff alleges that his position was filled by several employees who were decades younger than he was. Further, he accused Twitter of pushing an unfair amount of work onto him after he became ill with kidney stones; then, the company fired him because he could not do his job.</p>
    <p>This is not the first allegation that has been fired at Twitter and other similar social media sites with regards to age discrimination. Tech companies in California and other states have found themselves in difficult legal situations after posting job listings requesting only "new graduates." One former Google worker received a multimillion-dollar settlement after he was subject to pejorative comments from his coworkers and supervisors, who called him "obsolete" and "too old to matter."</p> <p>This case is just another reminder of the dominant culture in the tech industry, which tends to discriminate not only because of age but also because of gender and ethnicity. This collegiate culture leads companies into legal hot water, but age discrimination continues to pop up throughout Silicon Valley and other areas of innovation. No one should have to lose a job simply because they are errantly thought to be "too old" to adapt to or create new technology.</p> <p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b> Slate, "<a href="http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2014/07/15/twitter_sued_for_age_discrimination_it_s_not_uncommon_in_silicon_valley.html" target="_blank">Former Twitter Employee Sues the Company for Age Discrimination</a>" Alison Griswold, Jul. 15, 2014 </p>
