    <p>Workers who have become pregnant may have some extra assurance that they will get the assistance that they need, according to recent guidelines that were put out by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. Similar issues will soon be seen by the U.S. Supreme Court, as well, so it is important for all workers to understand the outcomes and what they could mean for their rights. As their legal rights change or are reinforced, they must remain knowledgeable about how these things can impact them on the job.</p> <p>The guidance being given out by the EEOC is directly related to the Pregnancy Discrimination Act.</p>
    <p>For example, one of the big statements being made is that workers who are pregnant should be allowed to take on jobs that are considered to be "light-duty." If other workers, who are not pregnant, have this work open to them, then it should not be denied to those who are.</p> <p>This is important because it seems to go against a decision made by the Fourth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, which said that light duty work could be made an option for some non-pregnant workers without any requirement that the same jobs be offered for those who have become pregnant. This ruling is now going to be reviewed, per an agreement made on the first of July, by the Supreme Court.</p> <p>If employees in California ever feel that their employer has committed a <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Discrimination/Disability.shtml">failure to make reasonable accommodations</a> if they are pregnant, they should know about their legal options to get the employer to comply. The outcome of this Supreme Court case will help to outline what can be done.</p> <p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b> Bloomberg BNA, "<a href="http://www.bna.com/eeoc-issues-new-n17179892312/" target="_blank">EEOC Issues New Enforcement Guidance on Pregnancy Bias</a>" Jul. 15, 2014 </p>
