    <p>California news outlets are reporting that a former Walgreens employee who was fired for taking a package of chips during a diabetic emergency will receive an $180,000 settlement. The diabetic woman, 57, had been employed by the company for nearly 18 years when the incident occurred. She reportedly took and ate a bag of chips that cost less than $2 in order to prevent herself from experiencing a medical emergency. The company will pay for the <a href="&rdquo;http:/www.nosratilaw.com/Discrimination/Disability.shtml&rdquo;">disability discrimination</a>, along with the costs of lost wages and emotional distress.</p> <p>Official reports show that the woman&rsquo;s condition was known by the company. She had a serious attack of hypoglycemia during a work shift in 2008. After she started to shake and sweat, the woman grabbed and ate a bag of chips to prevent her condition from escalating. Even though she paid for the chips after recovering from the attack, Walgreens still fired her for eating food sold in the store without first paying for it. The woman has been unemployed since that time.</p>
    <p>A settlement was reached shortly before the case was slated to go to trial. The company had attempted to have the suit dismissed, but a judge determined that there was no other evidence of misdeeds that would warrant the woman being fired. In addition to paying the settlement, Walgreens has agreed to provide training for workers at its facilities about accommodating disabled employees.</p> <p>Workers who have been the targets of disability discrimination may suffer from a variety of health conditions. These victims may not always look disabled, but they still deserve protection. No one should be forced out of a job for taking emergency life-saving measures while at work.</p><p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b>Source: SF Gate,&nbsp;"<a href="http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Walgreens-to-pay-diabetic-who-needed-food-fast-5596185.php" target="_blank" >Walgreens to pay diabetic who needed food fast and was fired</a>,"&nbsp;Bob Egelko,&nbsp;July 3, 2014</p>
