    <p>In a landmark employment law case, the California Supreme Court decided that undocumented immigrants should be protected from discrimination even if they illegally use other people's Social Security numbers to obtain a job.</p> <p>This significant ruling, designed to protect employees from <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Wrongful-Termination/Retaliation.shtml" >retaliatory discharge</a>, came after the high court decided that workers should be protected regardless of their immigration status. Workers are permitted to seek financial compensation for back pay up to the time when the employer discovered that the employee did not have legal status.</p> <p>A worker filed the civil suit against his former employer, arguing that he had been the victim of discrimination because of his disability. The chemical company that employed the man was able to get that workers' compensation case dismissed after it was determined that the plaintiff obtained the job with someone else's Social Security number. The court decided that the onus of responsibility for legal employment lies with the worker. That is, the employee is liable for the misdeeds that come along with fraudulently obtaining employment -- the company should still be required to pay the worker.</p>
    <p>This plaintiff's case will be sent back to a lower court because his immigration status is actually not entirely clear. Although the man used someone else's information to obtain the job, it has not been established that he is actually an illegal immigrant. This man, unlike many others, is one of the few undocumented immigrants to actually exercise his employment rights.</p> <p>Experts say that although this is a seminal ruling, it is unlikely to have a significant impact on a large number of cases. The fact remains that few undocumented immigrants actually seek compensation for wrongful failure to hire, even though they could be entitled to compensation. Illegal immigrants who believe they have been the victims of employer retaliation or wrongful termination may be entitled to damages because of their experiences.</p><p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b>Los Angeles Times, "<a href="http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-job-protections-illegal-immigrants-20140626-story.html" target="_blank">Job protections extend to immigrants using false ID, court rules</a>," June 26, 2014.</p>
