    <p>California is one of just a small number of states to provide official workplace discrimination protection for employees who are lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender. A new executive order from President Obama could cause such protections to become more widespread, however, providing additional support to those who are suffering <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Discrimination/" >workplace discrimination</a> because of their sexual orientation. The federal executive order would require contractors that provide services to the government to bar discrimination based on gender identity and sexual orientation.</p> <p>Federal workers already enjoy this particular type of protection, though workers in other industries are generally left out in the cold. A minority of U.S. states -- California among them -- offer protections for LGBT workers. Even though California has its own state mandates, experts say that the federal order could actually bolster protections for LGBT workers. The executive order would add another barrier to discrimination and limit the amount of taxpayer money that is spent on contractors with discriminatory hiring and working practices.</p>
    <p>Legal gurus say that existing laws provide an important framework for ending hostile work environments perpetrated against LGBT workers. However, employers are not always held responsible for actually following those laws. This is evidenced in the fact that about one in five LGBT employees reports unfair workplace discrimination because of their sexual orientation.</p> <p>No worker should have to suffer through the shame and embarrassment of workplace discrimination because of his or her gender identity or sexual orientation. These employees deserve the same type of fair treatment that is provided for protected groups of various racial compositions. Workers who have been victimized by this type of discrimination in California may be eligible for legal redress, including financial damages for workplace complaints.</p> <p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b> The Sun, "<a href="http://www.sbsun.com/social-affairs/20140621/executive-order-could-bolster-california-lgbt-worker-protections" target="_blank">Executive order could bolster California LGBT worker protections</a>" Brenda Gazzar, Los Angeles Daily News, Jun. 21, 2014 </p>
