    <p>A Disney worker who had spent 22 years at the company is alleging age discrimination in a wrongful termination suit. The man, who lost his job in 2013, has filed the suit in California, arguing that Disney has a troubling pattern of systematic <a href="http://www.nosratilaw.com/Discrimination/" >workplace discrimination</a>. In many instances, older workers have been intentionally terminated so that younger workers could take their place, saving the company money because of lower salaries.</p> <p>The plaintiff in this case says that he was told that his job position was eliminated because Disney was simply making fewer movies. There has not been any evidence to support that claim. Instead, the man says that he was replaced by his boss's assistant, who is only in her 20s or 30s. The man's job was even posted electronically after his departure. When he tried to apply, he was told that the position was already filled.</p>
    <p>The man says that his case is strengthened by the fact that another story department employee, age 69, was dismissed just seven months after his own termination. The victim was first hired in 1987, gaining full-time status in 1998. He became the head of the story department in 2005, where he consistently received positive performance reviews. A letter to the chairman of Walt Disney Studios resulted in a dismissive response; the executive said he was "impressed" with the man's dedication to Disney, but he never offered to meet with the terminated worker.</p> <p>The fact remains that although gender and race discrimination have received a lot of attention in recent years, age discrimination is far more subtle and insidious. Workers who believe they have been fired simply to save their employers money have a right to be financially compensated for the wrongful termination. These plaintiffs may be able to recover damages for distress and discomfort, emotional pain and a variety of other civil complaints against their employers.</p> <p> <b>Source:&nbsp;</b> The Hollywood Reporter, "<a href="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/disney-sued-age-discrimination-by-711235" target="_blank">Disney Sued for Age Discrimination by Former Story Department</a>" Alex Ben Block, Jun. 11, 2014 </p>
